## Start with the next useful move

Not every concern needs a high-stakes conversation. A clear first event may need brief feedback. Missing context needs inquiry. A capability gap may need coaching or training. An unclear system needs repair. A repeated pattern may need documentation and formal support.

## Observation before evaluation

Prepare the facts a camera, calendar, or work artifact could support. State the context, behavior, and work impact without pretending you know intent. Replace “bad attitude,” “not strategic,” and “poor communicator” with the event that caused concern.

## Context without surrendering the standard

Ask what the person saw and listen for information that could change your understanding. New context can explain intent, reveal a system problem, or correct your facts. It does not automatically erase impact. Say what changed in your view and what expectation remains.

## A request someone can perform

Ask for an observable alternative connected to the work: raise delivery risk at the checkpoint; let the speaker finish; bring options and a recommendation; use the decision channel before reversing a call. A personality transplant is not a useful request.

## Emotion changes pace, not dignity

Pause when emotion is high. Offer a break or a specific resumption time. Do not diagnose tears, argue with defensiveness, or demand immediate gratitude. Keep the message factual and use the correct support process when protected, medical, safety, or policy issues arise.

## Follow through proportionately

Agree on ownership, timing, and what evidence will show change. Recognize improvement. If a clear pattern continues after support and feedback, use your organization’s formal process rather than inventing a private escalation ladder.

> **Boundary:** this material is jurisdiction-neutral educational preparation. HR, legal, safety, security, safeguarding, and emergency support take precedence when the situation requires them.
